close_symbols: (event-callback dispatch / registration functions invoked by OS_NotifyEvent, if any)
explanation: To prove absence of direct or indirect recursion we must inspect every function the target calls and their transitive callees to see whether any path returns to OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. • OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish — Direct callee. Its implementation must be examined to see if it (or anything it calls) calls OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. • OS_NotifyEvent — Direct callee. Its implementation must be examined to see if it (or anything it calls) calls OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. In particular OS_NotifyEvent may invoke application callbacks which could (statically or via function pointers) call back into OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew/OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew, creating indirect recursion. • OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken — Callee of OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (per the static graph). Must be checked for any call (direct or via function pointers) back to OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. • OS_Lock_Global and OS_Unlock_Global — Callees of OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish. Must be checked as they could (in their implementations or through callbacks) call back to the target. • (event-callback dispatch / registration functions invoked by OS_NotifyEvent, if any) — If OS_NotifyEvent dispatches to registered handlers via function pointers, those registration/dispatch functions and the registered handlers (or their prototypes) must be inspected to determine whether a callback path exists back to OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew. Inspecting these symbols (and any further transitive callees they reference) is sufficient to determine whether OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew can reach itself directly or indirectly.
